Indian Stocks Post Steepest Weekly Gain in Six; Reliance Leads

-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w   a n d   S a n t a n u   C h a k r a b o r t y
-- 
2011-10-14T10:18:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-14/india-stocks-set-for-steepest-weekly-gain-in-six-reliance-rises.html
Indian stocks climbed, with the
benchmark index completing its steepest weekly advance in more
than a month, on expectation corporate earnings will withstand a
global economic slowdown.  Reliance Industries Ltd. gained after options protecting
against losses in the shares fell to the lowest in two years
before India’s most valuable company reports earnings tomorrow.
 Tata Consultancy Services Ltd. (TCS) , the largest software services
exporter, rallied for the third day. DLF Ltd., the nation’s
biggest developer, dropped for the first time in seven days
after it was downgraded by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and BNP
Paribas Securities ( Asia ).  The BSE India Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose 190.53, or
1.1 percent, to 17,074.45, according to preliminary closing
prices at 3:30 p.m. in Mumbai. The gauge surged 5.2 percent this
week, the most since the week ended Sept. 2. The measure reached
a three-week high on Oct. 12 after Infosys Ltd., the nation’s
second-biggest software maker, reported net income that beat
forecast, improving the outlook for company earnings.  The S&P CNX Nifty Index on the National Stock Exchange of
 India  Ltd. added 1.1 percent to 5,132.30. Its October futures
settled at 5,141.50. The BSE-200 Index increased 0.8 percent.  Overseas investors bought a net 1.83 billion rupees ($37.3
million) of Indian equities on Oct. 11, paring their outflow
this year to 23.6 billion rupees, according to  data  from the
market regulator. They withdrew a net $2.4 billion in August,
the most since October 2008.  To contact the reporters on this story:
